One or more concurring external mechanisms must be invoked to explain all evidence, and several have been proposed (e.g. 
 Ebi et al., 2001; 
 Grais et al., 2003; 
 Grais et al., 2004; 
 Liao et al., 2005; 
 Viboud et al., 2004; 
 Baker et al., 2020). These include, but are not limited to, weather-related temperature and humidity oscillations on the Earth (e.g. 
 Baker et al., 2020), the observed yearly pattern of air travel (e.g. 
 Grais et al., 2003, but see also 
 Grais et al., 2004), indoor heating during winter (e.g. 
 Liao et al., 2005), and bulk aerosol transport of virus through global convective currents or related to weather oscillations like “El Niño” (e.g. 
 Ebi et al., 2001; 
 Viboud et al., 2004).
